<p>
5a. Phonemic Awareness. Source: Chapter 14 of the Pressley text. Explanation: The awareness that words are composed of separate sounds, or phonemes, and that these are combined to form pronouncable words. It is phonemic awareness which is one of the best predictors of early reading sucess. If a child demonstrates low phonemic awareness by age 4-6, reading difficulties can be predicted. On the other hand, good readers demonstrate high levels of phonemic awareness.
<p>
5b. Lographic (Visual Cue) Reading. Source: Chapter 14 of the Pressley text. Explanation: This type of reading involves using visual information (or cues) associated with a word as opposed to simply utilizing "letter-sound correspondences". For example, a child may be able to read the word "STOP" when it is on a red hexagon, yet may not be able to read the same word when it is out of this type of context.
<p>
5c. Alphabetic Reading. Source: Chapter 14 of the Pressley text. Explanation: This type of reading involves the traditional "sounding out of words using letter sound relations". This process begins even before children know all of the letter sound correspondencies. In order to do this type of reading, the child must have attained a certain level of the previously explained concept of phonetic awareness, because "knowing about letters, their names, and sounds may not be suficient if the student does not possess phonetic awareness".
<p>
5d. Orthographic Reading. Source: Chapter 14 of the Pressley text. Explanation: This type of reading is utilized when the reader begins to perceive meaningful letter strings as wholes. For example, the reader perceives prefixes and suffixes as functional units as opposed to individual letters or sounds. This occurs only after the child has gained experience with alphabetic reading and has come to automatize certain letter combinations as meaningful wholes.
<p>
<br>
6. If I were teaching reading to first grade children, I would first test their level of awareness that words are composed of separate sounds (phonetic awareness). For children achieving scores that indicated a low level of phonemic awareness, I would provide additional instruction involving how to categorize words based on their sounds, how to identify common sounds, and how to identify non-similar sounds in games such as "odd one out".
<p>
After this initial test, and additional instuction for those students who needed it, I would begin my course on reading by teaching the children to recognize words by providing appopriate visual information (cues) associated with them (lographic reading). For example, I may make flashcards on which the word I am teaching the children to recognize is accompanied by a visual representation, or picture, of the word. The word dog would be accompanied by a picture of a dog and the word banana would be accompanied by a picture of a banana. In this way, the children would begin to recognize words by associating them with their visual representations.
<p>
<br>
After the children have reached a certain level of mastery of lographic reading, I would then lead them through the process of reading word by sounding them out (alphabetic reading) by using their letter sound relations. I would begin with simple and phonetically correct words such as cat, car, etc. Once they have mastered the sounding out of simple words, I would then lead them through the same task with words a bit more difficult, such as letter, color, etc.
<p>
 
Once the children can sound out words utilizing the alphabetic reading process, I would move on to teaching the child to peceive meaningful letter strings as wholes (orthographic reading). This would invlolve helping the child to recognize that certain letter combinations, which by this time the child has automatized, carry certain meanings. For example, the child would be taught to recognize that the suffix -ing, ed, and s carry standard units of meaning in every word in which they are present.
<p>
<br>

