5a.  Emergent Literacy.  Source:  Pressley.  Explanation:  A lot of literacy development occurs during the preschool years, which is a period of emergent literacy.  It can be seen in the reading and writing behaviors during the preschool years, and eventually develops into conventional literacy.  Good emergent literacy environments typically include rich interpersonal experiences with parents and siblings, plenty of literacy materials, and a high regard by parents for literacy and its development in children.


5b.  Storybook Interactions.  Source:  Pressley.  Explanation:  Storybook interactions are rich discussions and animated conversations between the reader and the child.  The adult and child discuss the meaning of the text, there is modeling of dialogue by adults, and positive reinforcement for the child who tries to get meaning from the pictures and the print.  Both the child and the adult relate what is happening in the text to their lives and the world around them.


5c.  Phonemic Awareness.  Source:  Pressley.  Explanation:  Phonemic awareness is awareness that words are made up of separable sounds (phonemes), and those sounds are combined to say words.  Children who lack phonemic awareness have trouble learning to spell and learning to understand letter-sound relationships.  Poor readers of all ages are typically less phonemically aware than similar-aged good readers.


5d.  Logographic Reading.  Source:  Pressley.  Explanation:  Logographic reading is sometimes referred to as visual cue reading.  It involves using only certain visual characteristics of a word to decode it, rather than relying on letter-sound correspondences.  Children who rely on logographic reading form an association between the visual cue and the word.


6.  My most important teaching opportunity is helping my 18-month-old toddler get a good start on learning.  We’ve been reading to Connor since before he was born.  We read at least one book before he leaves for daycare in the morning, and he usually demands at least three books at night before he’ll go to sleep.  By making books constantly available to him, taking the time to read to him daily, and letting him see that books are also important to his parents, we have created a positive environment for emergent literacy.  (He has enjoyed Pressley’s book, although he has been compelled to add his own drawings due to the lack of pictures).  Connor’s language skills are just beginning to show, so our discussions about the books we read together are very limited so far.  Despite his language limitations he is able to understand considerably more than he is able to verbalize, so our book reading sessions deviate considerably from the text.  I talk about the pictures, relate pictures in the text to real-world objects, such as our cat, various toys, and other items around the house.  As he matures, I intend to utilize storybook interactions with him, using scaffolding techniques to help him get meaning from the pictures and the print.  We’ll also work on phonemic awareness, beginning with letter recognition in books and the real world.

